Two people injured in a road crash at the border of Elgeyo Marakwet and Uasin Gishu counties were referred to private hospitals on Wednesday, due to the ongoing doctors' strike.A matatu hit a private car in the accident on Iten-Eldoret road on Tuesday evening.The casualties were turned away when they were taken to Iten County Referral Hospital.Patients were also asked to seek medical services at the Kapsowar mission facility, 50 km away.Resident Francis Cheruiyot said two prematurely delivered babies were moved in incubators as there were no nurses to attend to them.Read: Bungoma watchman delivers baby, two dead in NaivashaAlso read: Man dies at Kinango hospital gate, two more at Coast facilityDoctors and nurses in Elgeyo Marakwet said they will carry on with the nationwide strike even after it is called off.Benson Biwott, the county's Kenya National Union of Nurses secretary, said the county government has failed to tackle challenges unique to them.Biwott also accused Alex Tolgos' government of not creating a conducive environment for health workers.&ldquo;We have waited patiently since 2013 for this county to address our grievances. We will continue to down our tools even if a return-to-work formula to end the nationwide strike is signed today,&rdquo; he said.He added that the county's medics are overworked as no others have been hired.Elgeyo Marakwet has 381 nurses and 99 clinical doctors, operating in its 127 health facilities.Read: Doctors begin 'longest strike in history' over 2013 CBA agreementBiwott said the county's Public Service Board has instead frequently transferred nurses and doctors without paying their allowances.But Deputy Governor Gabriel Lagat dismissed him saying a series of meetings had been held but that solutions had not been found.Lagat said some of the county's hospitals were open as they were being manned by senior doctors in management positions.&ldquo;We have done everything in our power to restore normalcy,&rdquo; he said.Read: Hundreds stranded, moved to private hospitals in Baringo, MalindiAlso read: As doctors strike continues, KOT demand Uhuru help to stop deaths